<h2>Why Add a Clock to Your Website?</h2>

<p>[PLACEHOLDER — Discuss common use cases: event registration pages that show countdown or current time, scheduling pages for consultants and coaches showing their local time, time zone reference pages for global teams, and online exam portals that display the current time for test-takers.]</p>

<h2>How Embedded Clock Widgets Work</h2>

<p>[PLACEHOLDER — Explain the iframe: a small block of HTML code that loads a separate webpage inside your page. Clock widgets work by loading the clock's code in an iframe, so the clock runs independently inside your site. Explain that the clock reads time from the visitor's browser, not from a server, which means it shows local time automatically.]</p>

<h2>What to Look For in a Clock Widget</h2>

<p>[PLACEHOLDER — Cover: no ads (ads in an embedded widget appear on your page and reflect on your brand), lightweight (a heavy widget slows your page), responsive design (must look good on mobile), no third-party trackers, HTTPS support (required for modern browsers to allow iframes), and customizable appearance.]</p>

